The Minister of Power, Engr. Sale Mamman, yesterday met with the African Development Bank’s (AfDB’s) officials on the implementation of $410 million power transmission expansion projects. At a virtual meeting he held with the bank’s officials, the minister said there was also the Siemens Presidential Power Initiative, which was part of the government’s process of implementing the Nigerian Power Sector Roadmap to bridge the infrastructure gap in the power sector value chain. The minister’s spokesman, Aaron Artimas, quoted him in a statement issued on the meeting as saying that the government is committed towards the implementation of the Transmission Rehabilitation and Rehabilitation Programme (TREP) component funded by AfDB. The programme under the Transmission Company of Nigeria (TCN) is segmented into TREP 1 and TREP2. Dear our valued reader, we would like to hear your view about a membership club that we plan to launch. Kindly help us fill this survey. “Under TREP 1, we are already working on constructing 330kV Double Circuit transmission lines in various locations. We hope to expend $210 million on the phase,” Mamman said. In his remarks, the AfDB Nigeria Country Representative, Ebrima Faal commended the government on its power sector reform initiatives, describing the move as highly encouraging. He promised the development finance institution was committed to providing more strategic engagement to address the deficit in the nation’s power sector. TCN expanding transmission infrastructure through massive investment – MD FG to sink fresh N915bn loan into power sector Chad begs Nigeria for electricity supply